  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Richard Davis Webb presumably wrote this letter to Caroline Weston. Webb&apos;s interest in the anti-slavery cause and in America has never abated. The bulk of the English working class and the most eminent Englishmen have been &quot;all along on your side.&quot; Richard Cobden, who is &quot;the most eminent man in the nation, was always a staunch friend of the North.&quot; Webb also names Bright, Tennyson, Mill, Hughes, and Professor Newman as staunch supporters. John Elliott Cairnes came to Richard D. Webb&apos;s office in a state of exaltation about the fall of Richmond. Webb inquires about Caroline Weston&apos;s acquaintance. Webb sympathizes with Wendell Phillips in his views on Louisiana, but thinks it unwise of him to be so ready to quarrel with England.</subfield>
  </datafield>
